  <bioghist id="aspace_dc4ab9c03a07c45c4831b52d0a12b27b">
    <head>Biographical Note</head>
<p>Brian J. Purnell, Ph.D., is from New York City. He is Associate Professor of Africana Studies and History and Chair of the Africana Studies Department at Bowdoin College. Dr. Purnell received his Ph.D. in history from New York University in 2006 and was assistant professor of African and African American Studies at Fordham University before teaching at Bowdoin. At Fordham, he also worked as a research director of the Bronx African American History Project.</p><p>Dr. Purnell has focused his areas of study on U.S. Civil Rights and Black Power Movements and urban history. His Ph.D. dissertation was titled <emph>A movement grows in Brooklyn: the Brooklyn chapter of the Congress of Racial Equality (CORE) and the northern civil rights movement during the early 1960's</emph> and his first book was published in 2013: <emph>Fighting Jim Crow in the County of Kings : the Congress of Racial Equality in Brooklyn</emph>.</p>  </bioghist>
