  <scopecontent id="aspace_18c8c5c6366bd1cf5ca0faa9d3ce804d">
    <head>Scope and Contents</head>
<p>The Brian Purnell civil rights in Brooklyn research collection, 1914-2015, contains the research files from Dr. Brian Purnell's research on the Brooklyn chapter of the Congress of Racial Equality (CORE) and the Brooklyn branch of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP). Most of the materials are photocopies from archival collections held at the Center for Brooklyn History, other institutions, and privately owned, with some of Dr. Purnell's research notecards and annotations. Research was conducted between 2005 to 2015 and the photocopied materials date mostly from the 1940s to the 1970s. The archival collections represented are as follows:  </p><p>- National Association for the Advancement of Colored People Records (MSS34140) at the Library of Congress Manuscript Division. </p><p>- Rioghan Kirchner Civil Rights in Brooklyn Collection, 1960-2005 (BCMS.0011) at the Center for Brooklyn History.</p><p>- Arnie Goldwag Brooklyn Congress of Racial Equality (CORE) collection, 1943-2007 (ARC.002) at the Center for Brooklyn History.</p><p>- Olive and Marjorie Leeds paper held by their daughter Maxine Craig.</p><p>- Congress of Racial Equality. Brooklyn Chapter: Records (Mss 847) at the Wisconsin Historical Society.</p>  </scopecontent>
