are arranged in the order in which they were received from the donor.</p></arrangement><scopecontent id="aspace_1e113f9b237f62117632e4023424889b"><head>Scope and Contents</head><p>Series 3: Arnie Goldwag papers, 1962-1963, consists of one folder of photocopies from the Arnie Goldwag Brooklyn Congress of Racial Equality (CORE) collection, also held by the Center for Brooklyn History. The folder contains flyers and newspaper clippings related to the boycott of Ebinger's Bakery due to employment discrimination.</p></scopecontent><processinfo id="aspace_6aeeccd1c71eb52b052cfbc517695c02"><head>Processing Information</head><p>Duplicates of material in the Arnie Goldwag Brooklyn Congress of Racial Equality (CORE) collection (ARC.002) with no annotation have been discarded.</p></processinfo><c id="aspace_13d23583a1e0c1a2f7fc7dd90c8f952e" level="file"><did><unittitle>Ebinger's boycott</unittitle><unitid type="aspace_uri">/repositories/3/archival_objects/456948</unitid><unitdate datechar="creation" normal="1962/1963" type="inclusive">1962-1963</unitdate><container altrender="Record Carton" id="aspace_7b59d93da97cc1d7a66a5d3cf94c0cf1" label="Mixed Materials" type="Box">1</container><container id="aspace_2bd2555e25d8b8d57a2cf6f272b0b42d" parent="aspace_7b59d93da97cc1d7a66a5d3cf94c0cf1" type="Folder">25</container></did></c></c><c id="aspace_c55a1de75cb05305b75fc8f31e1fb25b" level="series"><did><unittitle>Series 4: Oliver and Marjorie Leeds papers</unittitle><unitid type="aspace_uri">/repositories/3/archival_objects/456922</unitid><unitdate datechar="creation" normal="1920/1998" type="inclusive">1920-1998</unitdate></did><arrangement id="aspace_5a55887c56cf9a7cd210cb3c41407420"><head>Arrangement</head><p>The materials in this series are arranged in the order in which they were received from the donor.</p></arrangement><scopecontent id="aspace_00113cb1d023fca216ac1f67fe5fe266"><head>Scope and Contents</head><p>Series 4: Oliver and Marjorie Leeds papers, 1920-1998, consists of photocopies of Oliver and Marjorie Leeds' papers, held by their daughter, Maxine Craig. Materials include biographical information, such as baptism and military records and obituaries, some correspondence, and their FBI files released via FOIA request. The records represent their work in the Brooklyn chapter of the Congress of Racial Equality (CORE) on the issues of housing, schools, transportation and traffic, and youth.</p><p>The Congress of Racial Equality, Brooklyn chapter records at the Wisconsin Historical Society were also from the Leeds' papers and donated to WHS by their daughter.</p></scopecontent><bioghist id="aspace_004ebc50e15ed36ecfae327f0b3a1510"><head>Biographical Note</head><p>Oliver Leeds was born June 5, 1920 to Thomas Leeds and Florence Copeland in the Bronx, New York. He married Marjorie Ansorge in 1954. He co-founded the Brooklyn chapter of the Congress of Racial Equality in 1962 and served as president. At the time of his death in 1989, Leeds was a proofreader at the Columbia Broadcasting System (CBS) and a member of the New York City Transit Authority Advisory Council.</p><p>Marjorie Leeds (nee Ansorge) was born on October 3, 1925 in Manhattan, New York. She served as treasurer in the Brooklyn chapter of CORE and was active in the Parent-Teacher Association of her childrens' school. She died on June 20, 1998. </p></bioghist><c id="aspace_ddcf9e3647c50c73949ff7cda78905ee" level="file"><did><unittitle>Miscellaneous (see Life Mag. article on Downstate)</unittitle><unitid type="aspace_uri">/repositories/3/archival_objects/456949</unitid><unitdate datechar="creation" normal="1963/1963">1963</unitdate><container altrender="Record Carton" id="aspace_4f29d949ece4fc9023ca45ab2cd099eb" label="Mixed Materials" type="Box">1</container><container id="aspace_93e70d0bfeeb7b243e991c9fc3abdcff" parent="aspace_4f29d949ece4fc9023ca45ab2cd099eb" type="Folder">26</container></did></c><c id="aspace_85b3d02279bbffb7630dcc4dd28dac96" level="file"><did><unittitle>Oliver Leeds military records and baptism records</unittitle><unitid type="aspace_uri">/repositories/3/archival_objects/456950</unitid><unitdate datechar="creation" normal="1920/1946" type="inclusive">1920-1946</unitdate><container altrender="Record Carton" id="aspace_5cf0078b0a792552006a7bbf13cf24dc" label="Mixed Materials" type="Box">1</container><container id="aspace_ddfd3daa8dcbe61cb7e9099450952c75" parent="aspace_5cf0078b0a792552006a7bbf13cf24dc" type="Folder">27</container></did></c><c id="aspace_2e6d1f349c8759695edc104396e8c751" level="file"><did><unittitle>ALP [American Labor Party] documents</unittitle><unitid type="aspace_uri">/repositories/3/archival_objects/456951</unitid><unitdate datechar="creation" normal="1953/1953">1953</unitdate><container altrender="Record Carton" id="aspace_db18c5b71ffe9268f32631536feafe83" label="Mixed Materials" type="Box">1</container><container id="aspace_d2d690403c8d06292d53ce98c3e4eed9" parent="aspace_db18c5b71ffe9268f32631536feafe83" type="Folder">28</container></did></c><c id="aspace_9b42ba91ce733767c04158f2c95556e3" level="file"><did><unittitle>CP [Communist Party] literature</unittitle><unitid type="aspace_uri">/repositories/3/archival_objects/456952</unitid><unitdate datechar="creation" normal="1947/1948" type="inclusive">1947-1948</unitdate><container altrender="Record Carton" id="aspace_392ff43ed61a38faf3f790a1ca973180" label="Mixed Materials" type="Box">1</container><container id="aspace_d9d31faa3736e689bca209cdbbd0e169" parent="aspace_392ff43ed61a38faf3f790a1ca973180" type="Folder">29</container></did></c><c id="aspace_c6fa9b6df2035646af190bf0f7e27e39" level="file"><did><unittitle>Oliver Leeds FBI file</unittitle><unitid type="aspace_uri">/repositories/3/archival_objects/456953</unitid><unitdate datechar="creation" normal="1951/1991" type="inclusive">1951-1991</unitdate><container altrender="Record Carton" id="aspace_a4100bf049f9aafe6a204382f19671ba" label="Mixed Materials" type="Box">1</container><container id="aspace_f